{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=July 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Kirsty Bentley | image = Kirsty-Bentley.jpg | caption= Kirsty shortly before her death. | birth_name = Kirsty Marianne Bentley | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1983|01|18}} | birth_place = [[Christchurch, New Zealand]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1998|12|31|1983|01|18}} | death_place = [[Canterbury, New Zealand]] | death_cause = [[blunt force trauma]] | body_discovered = 17 January 1999 | father = Sidney Bentley | mother = Jill Bentley }}
'''Kirsty Marianne Bentley''' was a teenager living in [[Ashburton, New Zealand]], who went missing while walking her family dog on the afternoon of 31 December 1998. After an extensive search lasting several weeks, her [[cadaver|body]] was found in dense [[scrubland|scrub]] approximately 40&nbsp;km away. [[New Zealand Police|Police]] consider the case to be a [[homicide]], and it remains one of the highest-profile [[cold case|unsolved murders]] in New Zealand.
== Early life == Kirsty Marianne Bentley was born on 18 January 1983 at the Christchurch Women's Hospital. She was the second child of her parents, Jill and Sidney Bentley; she had an older brother John.
Bentley was by all accounts a normal teenager. Her mother has described her as vibrant, honest and compassionate. She was confident and direct with people she knew, but could be shy and reserved with those she did not. Bentley had a strong creative streak that she expressed through [[drama]] classes and [[poetry]]. She attended [[Ashburton College]], and at school she was well liked and had a close-knit friend group. She had recently begun dating a local boy from one of her classes.<ref name="jill-book-2001">{{cite book |last1=Bentley |first1=Jill |last2=Williams |first2=Tony | date=2001 |title=Kirsty: Her Mother Writes with Love |location=New Zealand |publisher=Reed Books |isbn=978-0-7900-0790-8 }}</ref>
== Disappearance == [[File:Kirsty_Bentley_Disappearance_Area_Ashburton.jpg|thumb|right|The area near Chalmers Avenue, [[Ashburton, New Zealand|Ashburton]], which Bentley went missing from. The dog, Abby, was found tied up in the area of trees in the centre of the image.]] {{OSM Location map | coord = {{coord|-43.7|171.7}} | zoom= 9 | float = | width = 250 | height = 250 | scalemark = 80 | fullscreen-option = yes | caption = | title =
<!-- Last sighting--> | mark-coord1={{coord|-43.9144|171.7456}} | label1=Last sighting | label-size1 = 12 | label-color1 = | label-pos1 = top | shape1 = | mark1 =
<!-- Body found--> | mark-coord2={{coord|-43.5274|171.6717}} | label2= Body found | label-size2 = 12 | label-color2 = | label-pos2 = top | shape2 = | mark2 = | mark-size2 = }} On the day of her disappearance, Bentley met a friend at the Ashburton library at around 10:30am on 31 December 1998. After doing some shopping, they had lunch at [[McDonald's]] around midday.{{r|coronial-report|p=16}} Bentley was dropped off at her home by her friend's sister at around 2:30pm.{{r|jill-book-2001|p=20}}
After returning home, her brother John told her that her boyfriend had called and left a message, asking her to call him back. Phone records show she made a call to her boyfriend at 2:38pm,{{r|jill-book-2001|p=231}} but he wasn't there so she left a message asking him to call her back.
From here, it appears Bentley decided to take the family's black [[Labrador Retriever|Labrador]] dog,<ref name="press-jan-2">{{cite news |last1=Van Beynan |first1=Martin |last2=Gee | first2=David |date=1999-01-02 |title=Dog found tethered; copter joins search |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]]}}</ref> Abby, for a walk. This was not unusual for Bentley; she often took the dog for a walk to pass the time.<ref name="coronial-report">{{cite report |first=James |last=Ryan |date=2016-07-15 |title=An inquest into the death of Kirsty Marianne Bentley: Findings of Coroner J P Ryan }}</ref> John did not hear her leaving the house.{{r|jill-book-2001|p=232}} A neighbour witnessed her walking by his house with the dog at 3:05pm,{{r|jill-book-2001|p=233}} but from this point on the exact timeline of what happened to her cannot be clearly established.
== Search == Bentley's boyfriend called back at 4:30pm,{{r|jill-book-2001|p=19}}<ref name="press-jan9-weekender">{{cite news |last=O'Hanlon |first=Sinead |date=1999-01-09 |title=The mystery of Kirsty Bentley |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]]}}</ref> and at this time John noticed his sister was still absent. When his mother, Jill, returned home from work at around 5:15pm,{{r|jill-book-2001|p=13}} he immediately told her Bentley had not come home. After calling Bentley's boyfriend to confirm he did not know where Kirsty was, Jill conducted the first search, by walking the route Bentley would normally take down to the [[Ashburton River / Hakatere|Ashburton River]].{{r|press-jan9-weekender}} However, she was becoming increasingly anxious and soon decided to turn back.
After returning to the house, she and John agreed to wait until 6pm before conducting another search, in case Kirsty came home of her own accord. John left to search the dog walking route just before 6pm, and shortly afterwards Kirsty's father, Sid, returned home. When he was told Kirsty was missing, he immediately notified [[New Zealand Police|police]].{{r|jill-book-2001|p=22}}{{r|press-jan9-weekender}}
After Police became involved the search rapidly grew more intense throughout the evening, with a mixture of police staff, family members and friends canvassing the area looking for Bentley. This first search continued through the entire night. Nothing was found.{{r|coronial-report|p=6}}
The official [[Search and Rescue#New Zealand|Search and Rescue]] operation began at 8am the next day. At around 10am, the family dog, Abby, was found tied to a tree in a patch of dense foliage beside the Ashburton River,{{r|coronial-report|p=7}} close to Robilliard Park.{{r|jill-book-2001|p=34}} The general area had been searched the previous night, but the dog had not been found; the dense foliage means it is possible she was missed during this search. The dog was found tied to a tree with a lead of the same type that the family owned, however the family initially believed the lead did not belong to them.{{r|jill-book-2001|p=55}}
Nearby two items of clothing, underwear and boxer shorts, were found.{{r|jill-book-2001|p=36}} These were later confirmed to belong to Bentley.{{r|coronial-report|p=8}}<ref name="press-jan4-underwear">{{cite news |last=O'Hanlon |first=Sinead |date=1999-01-04 |title=Underwear find crushes parents |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]]}}</ref>
Over the next 16 days, police and volunteers meticulously searched the Ashburton area of [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]. Initially the search was focused on the Ashburton township but it expanded out to cover a much larger area of Canterbury. The [[New Zealand Army]] sent troops from [[Burnham, New Zealand|Burnham Military Camp]] to help in the effort also.<ref name="press-jan12-army">{{cite news |last=O'Hanlon |first=Sinead |date=1999-01-12 |title=Army helps in river search |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]]}}</ref>
== Discovery == [[File:Kirsty_Bentley_Body_Discovery_Area.jpg|thumb|right|The area of Camp Gully, [[Rakaia]], where Bentley's body was discovered.]] On 17 January, two men in the Camp Gully area of Rakaia, roughly 40&nbsp;km away from Ashburton, found a badly decomposed human body lying in a patch of overgrown scrub and planted pine.<ref name="press-jan18-bodyfound">{{cite news |last1=O'Hanlon |first1=Sinead |last2=Van Beynan |first2=Martin |date=1999-01-18 |title=Body find may end hunt for girl |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]]}}</ref> The body was later confirmed to be Bentley's.<ref name="press-jan21-bodyconfirmation">{{cite news |last=Bruce |first=Mike |date=1999-01-21 |title=Family devastated at news of Kirsty's murdered body |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]]}}</ref>
The body was lying at the bottom of a steep embankment,{{r|coronial-report|p=9}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Clausen |first=Victoria |date=1999-01-23 |title=Kirsty's killer 'familiar with the area'; Inquiry head rules out early resolution |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]]}}</ref> covered in a thin layer of branches and leaves.{{r|coronial-report|p=9}} She had been placed in the [[fetal position]] and was fully clothed in what she had last been seen wearing, with the exception of the underwear that had previously been found at the scene of her disappearance.{{r|coronial-report|p=10}}{{r|press-jan21-bodyconfirmation}} A large [[paddock]] was at the top of an embankment above her, and the location was close to [[New Zealand state highway network#Touring Routes|State Highway 72]], part of the [[Inland Scenic Route]].
The area she was found is known for being used by illegal [[cannabis]] growers, and the men who found her were out looking for a cannabis patch.<ref name="press-jan19-discoveryday2">{{cite news |last=O'Hanlon |first=Sinead |date=1999-01-19 |title=Family's painful wait; There is a chance it is Kirsty - policeman |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]]}}</ref> Initially they were reluctant to contact police, but decided the discovery was too important not to report.{{r|jill-book-2001|p=83}}
== Investigation == After the discovery, Police closed the scene and ordered a no-fly zone over the area as they conducted their investigation.{{r|jill-book-2001|p=80}} They conducted an extensive scene examination over several days, and took plaster casts of tire tracks in the area.{{r|press-jan19-discoveryday2}}<ref name="herald-jan-tracks">{{cite news |last=Wall |first=Tony |date=1999-01-19 |title=Clues to Kirsty case in tracks |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=1484 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |location=[[Auckland, New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref>
It was the height of summer, and so Bentley's body was in an advanced state of [[decomposition]].{{r|coronial-report|p=9}} She was recovered and transported to [[Christchurch Hospital]] where a [[autopsy|post-mortem]] was conducted.{{r|coronial-report|p=11}}{{r|press-jan19-discoveryday2}} It took three days before [[dental records]] were used to formally [[body identification|identify]] the body.{{r|jill-book-2001|p=81,85}}{{r|coronial-report|p=12}}
Bentley was killed by [[blunt force trauma]] to the right-side of the back of her head.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2016-07-16 |title=Coroner: Kirsty Bentley killed by massive blow to the head |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11675677 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |location=[[Auckland, New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref> The blow or blows was inflicted with enough force to severely fracture her [[skull]]. The pathologist determined she would have died shortly after the wound was inflicted.{{r|coronial-report|p=11}} Police initially withheld her cause of death from the public for operational reasons.{{r|press-jan21-bodyconfirmation}} The pathologist believed she was killed soon after she went missing, and likely placed in the Camp Gully area the same night, based on an examination of her stomach contents and the state of her body.{{r|coronial-report|p=16}}
Police asked for help from the public regarding vehicles that may have been seen in the area at the time.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=1998-01-29 |title=Police renew Kirsty call |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]]}}</ref> They also asked for [[cannabis]] growers to come forward if they had seen anything.<ref>{{cite news |last=Clausen |first=Victoria |date=1999-01-26 |title=Police appeal to growers of cannabis |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]]}}</ref> These calls to the public did not reveal anything useful.
== Funeral == A [[funeral]] for Bentley was held at St Stephen's Anglican Church in [[Ashburton, New Zealand|Ashburton]] on 25 January 1999.<ref name="press-jan26-funeral">{{cite news |last=O'Hanlon |first=Sinead |date=1999-01-26 |title=Tears of grief and anger for Kirsty |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]]}}</ref> Between 500 and 700 people attended.{{r|jill-book-2001|p=100}} Bentley's body was [[cremation|cremated]], and her ashes sealed in a steel urn. The urn was buried in a specially planted memorial garden at the family home. After Sid's death in 2015, the ashes were transferred to Bentley's mother, Jill.<ref name="press-2015-ashes-transfer">{{cite news |last1=Livingstone |first1=Tommy |last2=Sherwood |first2=Sam |date=2015-07-03 |title=Ashes returned to Kirsty's mum |url=http://www.pressreader.com/new-zealand/the-press/20150703/281638188864132 |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref>
== Media coverage == Media coverage of the case was extensive, making it one of the most high-profile unsolved crimes in New Zealand history. At the time, all major news outlets in New Zealand closely followed the case. The intensity of the coverage was both a help and a hindrance to the investigation. For instance, the men who found her body cited seeing Bentley's mother on evening news television broadcasts as the reason they had decided to come forward, despite the fact they were engaged in an illegal activity when they found her.{{r|jill-book-2001|p=83}}
However, the relationship between the media and the police and family would also be strained at times.{{r|jill-book-2001|p=134-139}} Decisions by media to publish reports that Bentley's body had been discovered before she had been formally identified were publicly criticised by police.<ref>{{cite news |last=Robinson |first=R J |date=1999-01-22 |title=Letters to the Editor: Identifying Kirsty |work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]] |location=[[Wellington, New Zealand]]}}</ref> In addition, the family expressed distress at the pressure they received from media during the several days that Bentley's body remained formally unidentified.{{r|jill-book-2001|p=84}}
== Suspects == Police have stated that hundreds of individuals have been considered suspects at one time or another, and a list of several hundred people have never been formally eliminated from the enquiry.<ref name="stuff-2017-tullylinked">{{cite news |last=Livingstone |first=Tommy |date=2017-03-15 |title=Mother of Kirsty Bentley not convinced new information in the case will bring answers |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/crime/90444218/Mother-of-Kirsty-Bentley-not-convinced-new-information-in-the-case-will-bring-answers |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref> At times the list of suspects has been as small as 20 people.<ref name="herald-2010">{{cite news |last=McCracken |first=Heather |date=2010-04-11 |title=New leads in Bentley murder case |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10637659 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |location=[[Auckland, New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref> Some possible suspects have received media attention in relation to the case.
=== Sid and John Bentley === At an early stage in the case, media reported that Sid and John were considered suspects in Kirsty's disappearance. Both denied any involvement, although John acknowledged in media interviews that it was only common sense that [[New Zealand Police|police]] should consider them as suspects.<ref>{{cite news |last=Martin |first=Yvonne |date=1999-01-16 |title=I'm a suspect, says Kirsty's big brother |work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion]] |location=[[Wellington, New Zealand]]}}</ref> Police later confirmed that they were considered suspects in the investigation.{{r|herald-2010}}
Police conducted a scene examination at the family home in the early stages of the investigation,<ref name="press-jan7-abduction">{{cite news |last=O'Hanlon |first=Sinead |date=1999-01-07 |title=Police search Kirsty's home; Abduction theory probed |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]]}}</ref> including carrying out [[Luminol]] testing.{{r|jill-book-2001|p=65}} However the tests did not find anything of value to the investigation.<ref name="press-jan8">{{cite news |last=O'Hanlon |first=Sinead |date=1999-01-08 |title=No new clues in search of home |work=[[The Press]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]]}}</ref>
Sid was unable to provide a strong [[alibi]] for his whereabouts on that day. He initially claimed he had been in [[Christchurch, New Zealand|Christchurch]] and [[Lyttelton, New Zealand|Lyttelton]] at the time, but later claimed he had hit his head on a cupboard door and forgotten that he had actually been in Ashburton for part of the day.{{r|herald-2010}}<ref name="stuff-2015-sid-death">{{cite news |last1=Livingstone |first1=Tommy |last2=Dally |first2=Joelle |last3=Mann |first3=Brittany |date=2015-07-01 |title=Cancer claims father of murdered Ashburton teen Kirsty Bentley |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/69832391/father-of-murdered-ashburton-teen-kirsty-bentley-dies |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref><ref name="stuff-2015-killerstillouthere">{{cite news |last=Livingstone |first=Tommy |date=2015-07-12 |title=Killer is still out here, says Bentley's mum |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/crime/70112815/killer-is-still-out-here-says-bentleys-mum |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref> His exact whereabouts at the time remain unknown. Family members have stated they believe Sid was embarrassed to admit whatever it was that he was doing on that day, but they do not believe he was involved in the murder in any way.{{r|stuff-2017-tullylinked|stuff-2015-killerstillouthere}}<ref name="stuff-2015-john-comments">{{cite news |last=Livingstone |first=Tommy |date=2015-07-02 |title=Kirsty Bentley's brother fears her murderer will never be caught |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/69898949/kirsty-bentleys-brother-fears-her-murderer-will-never-be-caught?rm=m |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref><ref name="newshub-tully-linked">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2017-03-15 |title=Kirsty Bentley killing: Russell John Tully linked to murder |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2017/03/kirsty-bentley-killing-john-tully-linked-to-murder.html |work=[[Newshub]] |location=[[New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref>
Police later consulted retired British [[Detective]] [[Inspector#United Kingdom|Inspector]] Chuck Burton, who stated that in his opinion, the perpetrator was likely to have known Bentley and been close with her, based on the nature of the crime and the way her body was left at Camp Gully.{{r|herald-2010}}
Despite this, police never laid [[criminal charge|charges]] against either Sid or John, suggesting no strong evidence of their involvement was ever found. In 2018, Police confirmed they do not believe Sid or John were involved in the crime.<ref name="stuff-dec-2018">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2018-12-02 |title=Developments in DNA testing could help finally solve 1998 murder of Ashburton teenager Kirsty Bentley |url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/new-zealand/developments-in-dna-testing-could-help-finally-solve-1998-murder-ashburton-teenager-kirsty-bentley |work=tvnz.co.nz |location=[[New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-12-03 }}</ref>
=== Green van === In the months after Bentley's death, Police asked the public for information about a green [[Commer FC|Commer van]], registration number EP9888, that was of interest to the inquiry.<ref name="herald-2000-greenvan">{{cite news |authors=NZPA |date=2000-06-30 |title=Van details fresh lead in Kirsty case |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=105425 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |location=[[Auckland, New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref> The van was described as a 1961 model set up to be used as a [[campervan|camper]], with a distinctive [[Commer]] branding badge attached to the front. The van was either blue or a faded blue-green. It was last registered with the [[NZ Transport Agency|NZTA]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://carjam.co.nz/car/?plate=EP9888 |title=Record for Registration EP9888 |date= |website=CarJam |access-date=2018-07-15}}</ref> This type of van was commonly used by tourists and drifters at the time, and in many cases these vehicles were not registered.{{r|herald-2000-greenvan}} The van was rare;<ref name="newscomau">{{cite news |last=Koubaridis |first=Andrew |date=2016-01-04 |title=Murder of teenager Kirsty Bentley has haunted New Zealand for 17 years |url=https://www.news.com.au/national/crime/murder-of-teenager-kirsty-bentley-has-haunted-new-zealand-for-17-years/news-story/34dfe08f63c622f7a81342c8b495e122 |work=[[News.com.au]] |location=[[Australia]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref> as few as 2 matching its general description are believed to have ever been in New Zealand.
An experienced mechanic originally reported the van to police after seeing it in the area around the time of Bentley's disappearance. Due to the distinctive nature of the van and the man's experience with them, he took special note of the van at the time and was able to give a highly detailed description of it. The van was also seen by other witnesses in the [[Ashburton, New Zealand|Ashburton]] area in the weeks before Bentley's disappearance, and there were reports it was also seen in the Camp Gully area.
Police believed that such a distinctive vehicle could not go unnoticed by the public, and a sighting could lead to a break in the case. Many people came forward to police with possible sightings, but all were discounted as not being the van that police were seeking; the distinctive nature of the van made it very easy for them to rule out mistaken sightings. No further leads on the camper were ever revealed, and it has never been found.{{r|newscomau}}
In addition to this, police distributed fliers asking for information on a girl seen near the van on Chalmers Avenue, close to where Bentley had disappeared. The girl was known to the [[Dairy (store)|dairy]] owners in the suburb of Netherby as a customer. However, despite this, and repeated public requests by police, the girl never came forward. Her identity and her connection to the suspicious van remains unknown.
=== Russell John Tully === In March 2017 media reported that police were investigating whether Russell John Tully, a local man who [[List of massacres in New Zealand|murdered two staff members]] at the [[Ashburton, New Zealand|Ashburton]] [[Ministry of Social Development (New Zealand)#Work and Income|Work and Income]] office in 2014, may have been involved.{{r|newshub-tully-linked}} Tully had been known to camp in the area of Ashburton Kirsty went missing from.<ref name="stuff-2018-tully-eliminated">{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Sherwood |date=2018-05-30 |title=Work and Income double murderer interviewed over Kirsty Bentley cold case |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/crime/104330963/work-and-income-double-murderer-interviewed-over-kirsty-bentley-cold-case |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |location=[[New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref> Tully strongly denied any involvement.{{fact|date=October 2018}}
In May 2018 Police announced they had eliminated Tully from the enquiry. He had provided a detailed account of where he had been living and working during the time Bentley disappeared. Police confirmed he had not originally been interviewed because he was living in [[Nelson, New Zealand|Nelson]] at the time, and was no longer suspected of any involvement.{{r|stuff-2018-tully-eliminated}}
=== Others === After Sid's death in 2015, an unidentified woman came forward to say that she suspected her ex-boyfriend had been involved in the murder. He had been a suspect in the original investigation, and they had both been interviewed by police and media at the time in relation to the case. According to an interview with her in 2015, her ex-boyfriend, while intoxicated, had admitted his involvement to her on several occasions.<ref name="herald-2015-woman-changes-statement">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2015-07-07 |title=Woman changes statement over Kirsty Bentley murder |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11477094 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |location=[[Auckland, New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref> It is unclear whether she ever came forward to formally change her statement to police.{{or?|date=October 2018}}
== Recent developments == In 2014 the case was transferred from [[New Zealand Police#Ranks|Detective Inspector]] Greg Williams to Detective Inspector Greg Murton. At the time he commented that the investigation was open and would continue to be until it was resolved.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2014-06-10 |title=Police 'will never give up' |url=http://www.guardianonline.co.nz/news/police-will-never-give-up/ |work=[[Ashburton Guardian]] |location=[[Ashburton, New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-07-15 }}</ref>
In 2015 Bentley's father, Sid, died of [[esophageal cancer]].{{r|stuff-2015-sid-death}} His death briefly renewed public interest in the case.{{fact|date=October 2018}}
In 2018, Police confirmed that Russell John Tully was no longer of interest to the enquiry.{{r|stuff-2018-tully-eliminated}}
In late 2018, almost 20 years after the disappearance, Detective Inspector Murton announced that there had been advances in DNA testing that he hoped could lead to a break in the case. Items of evidence including the dog lead and underwear have been submitted for further testing at [[Institute of Environmental Science and Research|Environmental Science and Research]].<ref name="herald-dec-2018">{{cite news |last=Bayer |first=Kurt |date=2018-12-02 |title=DNA could crack open Kirsty Bentley cold case 20 years after Ashburton schoolgirl's murder |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12168364 |work=nzherald.co.nz |location=[[Christchurch, New Zealand]] |access-date=2018-12-03 }}</ref>
The case is still under active investigation, with Detective Inspector Murton stating in 2018 that, "the case is still open and being investigated."{{r|herald-dec-2018}}
